Questions and answers

Michael Franke & Michael Henry Tessler

session 1

question 1

[Q] With respect to prior beliefs about \(\theta\) - when we assign \(\theta\) the value 0.5 : does it mean that we believe that the coin is fair / or neither fair nor biased?

[A] If we assume that \(\theta = 0.5\), i.e., we believe that \(P(\theta = 0.5) = 1\), we believe that the coin is perfectly fair, so that each outcome has exactly the same probability. A belief that the coin is might be fair or biased would assign some probability (mass) to the possibility that \(\theta = 0.5\) but also probability to other values for \(\theta\).

question 2

[Q] What do you mean when you say that Bayes theorem enables to reverse conditional probabilities?

[A] Look at how we can calculate the probability of data \(D\) given a vector of values for latent parameters \(\theta\) with Bayes rule:

\[\underbrace{P(\theta \, | \, D)}_{posterior} \propto \underbrace{P(D \, | \, \theta)}_{likelihood} \ \underbrace{P(\theta)}_{prior}\]
We have a “feedforward theory” of how a given \(\theta\) makes some \(D\) more or less likely; this is the likelihood function. We use Bayes theorem to reverse this relationship, in order to infer the “likely underlying causes” from the observable data.

question 3

[Q] How does the marginal likelihood enters the equation? What does it denote?

[A] We specified Bayes rule for data inference as:

\[\underbrace{P(\theta \, | \, D)}_{posterior} \propto \underbrace{P(D \, | \, \theta)}_{likelihood} \ \underbrace{P(\theta)}_{prior}\]
This is shorthand notation for:

\[P(\theta \, | \, D) = \frac{P(D \, | \, \theta) \ P(\theta)}{\underbrace{\int P(D \mid \theta') \ P(\theta') \text{d}\theta'}_{=P(D)}}\]

where the normalizing constant \(\int P(D \mid \theta') \ P(\theta') \text{d}\theta'\) is also called the marginal likelihood. It denotes the a priori likelihood of observing data \(D\) (obtained by marginalizing over all possible parameter values).

question 4

[Q] You talked about misconstrued interpretations of the \(p\)-value and said it can not be taken to be the likelihood that the null-hypothesis is true given your data. Did I misunderstand something? I’ve always thought of this as the definition for the p-Value.

[A] You are in excuisite company. Even many statistics lecturers misinterpret \(p\)-values (see this paper, for instance). Here is a simple intuitive argument that shows that \(p\)-values do not represent the probability of the null-hypothesis given the data.

No matter what you believe about my coin, as long as you do not already believe with absolute certainty that it is fair, would you be absolutely certain that it is if I flip it twice and we observe one outcome of heads? – I definitely would not yet rule out that it might not be a value slightly different from \(\theta = 0.5\), but the associated \(p\)-value is 1. (Interestingly, it is also 1 for the null-hypotheses \(\theta = 0.49\) and \(\theta = 0.51\). So if \(p\)-values gave you the likelihood of the null hypothesis, you should place probability 1 beliefs on mutually incompatible world states.)

session 2

[Q] While studying generative processes it was mentioned that the sample size plays a critical role in the outcome of the final distribution. So how do we know whether a given sample set is enough? Especially, since the process of calculating the marginal likelihood is also a computationally intensive process is there an objective way to calculate the sample size ?

[A] First of all, the computation of the marginal likelihood would only matter if we wanted to approximate a posterior/conditional probability distribution. But in fact, the inference algorithms used (such as MCMC, rejection etc.) are designed in such a way that they do not need to calculate the marginal likelihood.

So, how do you know that your sample size gives you an approximation that is good enough? – You might never know for sure. But suppose you take 1 million samples. Then you compare the results after 900,000 with those after 1 million. If you see no substantial difference (e.g., measured in terms a divergence between probability distributions), you probably do not need to collect more than 1 million samples.

Wait! How do I know that this one set of samples is representative? – You might never know for sure. That’s why (for some inference algorithms (like MCMC)) we would usually take at least two independent sets of samples and again quantify their divergence as a diagnostic.
